<DOC><DOCNO> AP880315-0110 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-15-88 1219EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p BC-ILLINOISAt-A-Glance     03-15 0319</FIRST><SECOND>BC-ILLINOIS At-A-Glance,</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from Illinois to attend the 1988 Democratic andRepublican national conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 15   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates:173 Super delegates: 15 TOTAL: 188   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 15   Selection of delegates:Tuesday, March 15 and Saturday, May 7      Illinois is a direct-election primary, meaning its 113congressional district delegates to the Democratic NationalConvention are elected directly from the primary ballot.   Ilinois Democrats will be faced with a two-part ballot in theMarch 15 primary. The top part of the ballot will be a non-bindingpresidential ``beauty contest,'' and the second part will list thecandidates for national convention delegate.   The remainder of the state's pledged national conventiondelegates will be picked by the State Central committee on May 7.They will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportionto the number of delegates from congressional districts pledged tothe candidates.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, March 15   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 92   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 15 and Thursday, June 16   Selection of delegates: Tuesday, March 15 and Thursday, June 16      Illinois Republicans have the same kind of two-part presidentialballot as the Democrats. The top part of the ballot is anon-binding presidential ``beauty contest,'' while the second partlists the candidates for national convention delegate.   The candidates for delegate can have the name of a presidentialcandidate printed next to their own name on the ballot.   Eighty-two delegates will be elected directly from the ballotand will be apportioned among congressional districts, ranging fromtwo to five delegates per district. The state's remaining 10delegates will be elected at-large at the state convention June16-18.</TEXT></DOC>